2 Went back to Scratch for the second time this Sunday and I think our love affair is over. I so don't want it to be, I am a firm believer of supporting any independent business, but it just wasn't working for me this time around. My last visit was a 3-star experience (for the food, the actual space to me is just OK, nothing special) and having spent the afternoon with out-of-towners in Scottsdale, thought it might be a nice little stop off before trotting back to my Chandler hood.  Upon arrival, we were greeted with dirty dishes on the outside table left from the previous diners, and several of the tables inside hadn't been cleared either. Not that busy inside so they definitely had time to clean up.  2 out of the 4 pastries we ordered weren't available, so we ended up sharing some sugar & butter crepes. Now I have to admit, they were pretty tasty and would have warranted a 3-star reaction if it wasn't for everything else being slightly off. My mother-in-law came out of the bathroom to declare that it looked like someone had been sick in the basin. Nice.  And I do agree with another reviewer that it seems slightly inappropriate/insensitive to have a picture of the burning twin towers displayed amongst the fashion shots on the wall. I know the owner is a brilliant photographer, but maybe this should be in his private collection.  Oh, by the way, the tables outside were still covered in dirty plates when we left 45 minutes later.
3 First of all, I don't find photographs of significant US history offensive - I mean Scratch isn't hanging a Hezbollah flag or anything, I think the previous reviewers need to calm down.  I had a light lunch in Scratch today, asparagus veloute with a salad for $7.50. The layout  and pastry display confused me a little, I thought this might be another "order at the corner then sit" deal, but the woman behind the counter set me straight and was prompt getting me situated. I asked her opinion on the soups, and she pointed out that both the asparagus and mushroom veloutes were made with chicken broth, but that they had a new vegetarian soup, Carrot Ginger. I was impressed because I hadn't even said I was vegetarian. But, ummm, I hate carrot soup, so I went ahead and did the unthinkable by ordering the asaparagus.   I had brought a book, so I chilled for a while, as well as checking out the artwork and the retail items. Apparently the soups are made to order, which hardly seems efficient for a restaurant, but it didn't take nearly as long to be served as I'd anticipated. The side of greens was fresh and a good complement to the thick creamy asparagus soup.   I am a soup aficionado and am usually upset to find a runny mess set in front of me, but this was just how I like it. The asparagus had not been overcooked and thus was not bitter at all, the soup was perfectly balanced. I would say that perhaps it was not as hot as I like soup, but that's my only complaint.   There's another front house employee at Scratch that is apparently the King of Awkward Jokes. When I entered I said I was in for lunch and he announced they don't serve lunch...beat...haha. Later I asked him for a water refill and he said they didn't have anymore water...beat...haha. Once was disconcerting, twice was just too much thank you.  Nonetheless, I would definitely come back to Scratch to try out the whole wheat savory crepes (smoked salmon and sour cream, yes please!) and desserts.
